@page "/projects"

<PageTitle>Projects</PageTitle>

<h1 class="page-heading">Projects</h1>
<p class="text-muted mb-4">A selection of games and projects I've worked on.</p>

<div class="row g-4">

    <div class="col-md-6">
        <div class="card project-card h-100">
            <div class="project-img-slider">
                <img src="@platformImages[platformIndex]" class="card-img-top" alt="Platform Ain't Platforming" />
                <button class="slider-btn slider-btn-prev" @onclick="() => platformIndex = (platformIndex - 1 + platformImages.Length) % platformImages.Length">&#8249;</button>
                <button class="slider-btn slider-btn-next" @onclick="() => platformIndex = (platformIndex + 1) % platformImages.Length">&#8250;</button>
                <div class="slider-dots">
                    @for (int i = 0; i < platformImages.Length; i++)
                    {
                        var idx = i;
                        <span class="slider-dot @(platformIndex == idx ? "active" : "")" @onclick="() => platformIndex = idx"></span>
                    }
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="project-card-header">
                <span class="project-type-badge">Game Jam</span>
            </div>
            <div class="card-body">
                <h5 class="card-title">Platform Ain't Platforming</h5>
                <p class="card-text">
                    This project was for a game jam, so it was built in a very short time frame.
                    The theme for the jam was "Its not a bug, its a feature", so I made a 3D platformer where some platforms have random effects applied to the player.
                    Some platforms might make you jump higher, some may move you in a random direction, and some may even change your speed!
                    It was a fun way to experiment with Unreal Engine's node-based scripting system, and I learned a lot about how to quickly prototype gameplay ideas.
                </p>
                <div class="project-tags mb-3">
                    <span class="project-tag">Unreal Engine</span>
                    <span class="project-tag">UE Nodes</span>
                    <span class="project-tag">3D Platformer</span>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="card-footer bg-transparent">
                <a href="https://ajgamess.itch.io/platform-aint-platforming" class="btn btn-sm btn-primary">Itch.io</a>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="col-md-6">
        <div class="card project-card h-100">
            <div class="project-img-slider">
                <img src="@infiniteImages[infiniteIndex]" class="card-img-top" alt="Infinite Station" />
                <button class="slider-btn slider-btn-prev" @onclick="() => infiniteIndex = (infiniteIndex - 1 + infiniteImages.Length) % infiniteImages.Length">&#8249;</button>
                <button class="slider-btn slider-btn-next" @onclick="() => infiniteIndex = (infiniteIndex + 1) % infiniteImages.Length">&#8250;</button>
                <div class="slider-dots">
                    @for (int i = 0; i < infiniteImages.Length; i++)
                    {
                        var idx = i;
                        <span class="slider-dot @(infiniteIndex == idx ? "active" : "")" @onclick="() => infiniteIndex = idx"></span>
                    }
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="project-card-header">
                <span class="project-type-badge">Capstone Project</span>
            </div>
            <div class="card-body">
                <h5 class="card-title">Infinite Station</h5>
                <p class="card-text">
                    This game is a survival game where the player has to survive AI enemies while repairing generators in a train station.
                    The goal is to make it as many floors as you can. With different enemies and new floors generating each time.
                    I wasn't able to fully get this completed during the capstone time but I had fun making the logic to allow the user to get random level picked from the random list.
                </p>
                <div class="project-tags mb-3">
                    <span class="project-tag">Unreal Engine 5</span>
                    <span class="project-tag">UE Nodes</span>
                    <span class="project-tag">3D Survival</span>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="card-footer bg-transparent">
                <a href="https://github.com/AJGamess/CapstoneProject" class="btn btn-sm btn-outline-primary me-2">GitHub</a>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="col-md-6">
        <div class="card project-card h-100">
            <div class="project-img-slider">
                <img src="@pkmImages[pkmIndex]" class="card-img-top" alt="Pokemon Battle Simulator" />
                <button class="slider-btn slider-btn-prev" @onclick="() => pkmIndex = (pkmIndex - 1 + pkmImages.Length) % pkmImages.Length">&#8249;</button>
                <button class="slider-btn slider-btn-next" @onclick="() => pkmIndex = (pkmIndex + 1) % pkmImages.Length">&#8250;</button>
                <div class="slider-dots">
                    @for (int i = 0; i < pkmImages.Length; i++)
                    {
                        var idx = i;
                        <span class="slider-dot @(pkmIndex == idx ? "active" : "")" @onclick="() => pkmIndex = idx"></span>
                    }
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="project-card-header">
                <span class="project-type-badge">Class Project</span>
            </div>
            <div class="card-body">
                <h5 class="card-title">Pokemon Battle Simulator</h5>
                <p class="card-text">
                    This was a project for my Object Oriented Programming class, where we had to create a console-based project in Java.
                    I decided to go with a Pokemon battle simulator, where the player can choose from a selection of Pokemon and battle against a computer opponent.
                    The game features a turn-based battle system, where each Pokemon has its own set of moves and stats. And it has typing advantages and disadvantages.
                    It was a fun way to practice my Java skills and learn about object-oriented programming concepts like inheritance and polymorphism.
                </p>
                <div class="project-tags mb-3">
                    <span class="project-tag">IntelliJ</span>
                    <span class="project-tag">Java</span>
                    <span class="project-tag">Console Simulator</span>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="card-footer bg-transparent">
                <a href="https://github.com/AJGamess/Pokemon-Battle-Simulator" class="btn btn-sm btn-outline-primary me-2">GitHub</a>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

</div>

@code {
    private int platformIndex = 0;
    private int infiniteIndex = 0;
    private int pkmIndex = 0;

    private string[] platformImages = {
        "Images/PlatformAintPlatforming2.jpg",
        "Images/PlatformAintPlatforming1.png"
    };

    private string[] infiniteImages = {
        "Images/InfiniteStation.jpg",
        "Images/InfiniteStation2.jpg"
    };

    private string[] pkmImages = {
        "Images/PKMBattleSim1.jpg",
        "Images/PKMBattleSim2.jpg"
    };
}
